<br>
The thread on the biblical support of wiccans touches on the fact that Christianity teaches the Golden Rule, do unto to others as you would have done unto you. Love your neighbors as you love yourself<br>
<br>
It teaches that we are to respect the right of others to live as they choose.  It teaches that we should love all men and not treat others badly because they dont believe like we do.<br>
<br>
That said, it also teaches that marrying people who believe like you do makes marriage alot easier ( I think we have discussed that idea already)<br>
<br>
I teach the 16-18 year olds in sunday school and I have several teen nieces and nephew (several of whom live outside of Utah where there are not alot of LDS around)<br>
<br>
The advice I give to them is that the reason you should only date LDS people ISN'T because LDS have a corner on the only nice people out there, it is precisely the opposite.  There are plenty of great people who are not LDS BUT you marry who you date. And if you date and fall in love with a person who isnt LDS then you can't get married in the temple.  On top of that, religion especially for LDS is a huge thing and to not have that in common with the person you spend your life with can only add stress to marriage.  <br>
<br>
So if you want to marry in the temple then it is best to date only LDS who hold the same values because you dont know who your going to fall in love with.  Why risk falling in love with someone who cant take you where you want to go.<br>
<br>
I admit my parents were very lax and my brothers,my sister and I dated who we wanted to and I dated about half LDS and half not.  Two guys I dated that at one time I was very serious about were 1. Catholic and 2. an inactive LDS who didnt have the same values and ideals that I have.  The Catholic was actually  forced to break up with me by HIS mother <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  because I was making him question his own religion, and #2 I broke his heart after we had talked about marriage because I knew that there were issues that were not resolvable. (Broke my heart too)  <br>
<br>
My sister married a guy who wasnt LDS but he was abusive and she later left (this is not a reflection on his religious choice, He was just a jerk period)<br>
<br>
I think marriage is tough enough at times without something as big as religion to disagree about. - Shirene <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FEFEFE><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> sweetpeas mommy</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#5F9EA0>(8/13/03 7:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=240.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   my .02</span><hr size=1> If it was the girl choosing to end the relationship because she didn't see their values as compatible, then I think I would see that as good sense. We all make such choices while dating because if you are going to be in a relationship, potentially for the rest of your life and potentially raising children together, holding the same values...whether those values stem Christianity, Islam, secular humanism, Hinduism, or whatever will likely help you to have a better relationship.<br>
<br>
When I was dating, I limited myself to mainline Christians because they were people who shared the value system I wanted to live my life by. But that wasn't the only criteria I had...I would not have continued a relationship with someone who told me he did not want to have children either...because I wanted to have children and I think it's important to agree on that aspect of your relationship. After all, there is no middle ground, you either have kids or you don't.<br>
<br>
Now in this situation, the parents seem to be making the choice for the girl. While as Stacy pointed out, that is their right, it is not the way I would choose to parent. Especially at 15, forbiding the relationship is likely to backfire anyway, so for me, I would encourage my dd to think about what she is looking for from a relationship (does she want to get married, have kids, etc.) and then think about the values she thinks are important to share based on what you want in the future (not just at 15). <br>
<br>
I had friends who were very strict religiously and in every other way and usually those kids ended up rejecting the system their parents wanted them to embrace. So unless we viewed the relationship as a threat to our child's safety, I don't think my dh and I would forbid it outright, though we would encourage her to think about what she is looking for. <br>
<br>
But we also don't know the whole situation either...maybe the parents didn't like the kid's attitude...maybe he told them he thought their religion was crap...or maybe the parents just are  overly strict. Who knows.<br>
<br>
But I don't think in general that dating or not dating a person based on whether they share your religious or other values is inherently intolerant. And if it is, I suspect it is an intolerance we all have -- Christian or not. I doubt I would have had a very good marriage if I had married an atheist who did not want me to raise our children Christian just as Shirene would not have had a happy marriage outside the LDS temple and just as I doubt Stacy would have been very happy married to a Born Again Christian who wanted to raise any children to accept Jesus.<br>
<br>
Kerrie-Anne  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#EFEFEF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=monynh>monyNH</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#5F9EA0>(8/13/03 7:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=240.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   My own thoughts</span><hr size=1> I don't know that Xianity teaches intolerance so much as Xianity gives a front to people who are intolerant anyway.  What I mean is, one doesn't need a Bible to be a bigoted asshole, but the Bible can be interpreted by some in such a way as to give a cover or an excuse for one's bigotry.  In the same way, the Bible can be interpreted by some in such a way as to encourage the acceptance and embracing of a minority group.  Xianity is a tool whereby individuals can manipulate the thinking of some who already have a propensity to be hateful and intolerant.  But I don't think Xianity does by default encourage intolerance.  We've spoken before about how contradictory and wishy-washy Biblical teachings are, and so I think the Bible itself lacks the conviction to be a racist manifesto.<br>
<br>
-Simone <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FEFEFE><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 438<br> <font color=#5F9EA0>(8/13/03 7:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=240.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: I think we're still missing the core issue </span><hr size=1> which is not about whether it's optimal to date and marry someone who shares your beliefs (which I TOTALLY agree with), rather it is around whether religion, and xianity in particular teaches intolerance.<br>
<br>
Now while both xians who responded said the didn't specifically prohibit dating another faith, I do think it's interesting to note that Kerrie-Anne did say<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So unless we viewed the relationship as a threat to our child's safety, I don't think my dh and I would forbid it outright,<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
and it's exactly the threat to a child's salvation and spiritual path that I think these LDS parents and others such as the JW's have in mind when prohibiting social contact or dating with other faiths. I know Kerrie you may not be talking about this, but surely it would disturb you if your daughter dated a guy you thought was going to burn in hell for more reasons than that they would have epistomological disagreements...<br>
I might worry as an atheist too, but I wouldn't see it as a threat to my dd's immortal sould or the spiritual path of her children and so perhaps that's why I see those of other faiths as less threatening and therefore am more tolerant (also I am not following the commands of an intolerant god, but that's a given<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
And Kerrie-Anne--<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But I don't think in general that dating or not dating a person based on whether they share your religious or other values is inherently intolerant.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I have to agree with this generally and that marrying someone who shares your views seems wise, but I think the dating thing was a springboard to the real question which was whether religion teaches intolerance. We can go to public schools, politics, social situations etc. to find MANY examples of xian intolerance from prohibitions on gay unions to forced prayer/pledges to god in schools to publicly funded xian prayers and celebrations. This same monetary and social support is simply not afforded other religions or atheists for that matter and xian children are indeed taught that they are “saved” or worse that they are saved while others will burn eternally in hell. It may be argued xians are merely following the guidelines of an intolerant deity, but it is still intolerance whether dictated “from above” or derived from man. I don’t see any refutation of this so far.<br>
<br>
The Golden Rule would mean it would be okay and perhaps ethical for me to beat you if I am a masochist or encourage you to do cocaine if I would like the same. I could extrapolate this into gay marriage/rights, women's rights/roles, SOCAS etc. It's the reason so many xians feel proselytizing and missionary work is justifiable--besides following another of god's commandments to expand the religion and witness, xians feel they would want someone to proselytize to them so it's okay to do it to others. They want someone to pray in school and use their tax money to pledge to their god so it's okay to do it to my children with my money (this never seems to work the other way, but it still follows the spirit of the Golden Rule.<br>
No--give me the Wiccans and their (is it the Silver Rule?) Creed which asks that you not do unto others as you would not have done unto you. I would NOT like my tax money spent to force religious instruction not of my choosing on my child and force her to pray to a false god...my bet is xians would NOT want this either (Imagine a prayer to Satan every school morning<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ...If only they could follow the Wiccan Creed...but see the Wiccans don't believe we will burn in hell forever or be rejected eternally from salvation by a vengeful god with a rudimentary and barbaric justice system so that right there makes them more tolerant.<br>
<br>
