<br>
It's English, not Latin. It's a living language. That means that definitions can change. If we change our laws to allow gays to marry, than &quot;marriage&quot; will mean &quot;an institution whereby two adults are joined.&quot; <br>
<br>
Websters doesn't create the meaning, it simply <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>reports</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> it. Change the law and Websters will follow.<br>
<br>
The difference between you &quot;not budging&quot; on gay marriage and a vegan &quot;not budging&quot; on animal products is, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>the vegan isn't trying to legally FORCE you and everyone else to stop using animal products.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> The vegan is minding her own business, saying &quot;I personally choose not to eat animal products because I think it's wrong.&quot; Just as you didn't marry another woman because you think it's wrong. <br>
<br>
That's very different from saying that those who think it's right should be legally blocked from marrying the person they love, so that religious people can force their religion's restrictions on non-adherents. What you are doing is more like our theoretical vegan saying &quot;everyone should be forbidden to use animal products, because *I* think it's wrong, and I can <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>prove</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> it's wrong because it says so right here in my bible,<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Diet for a New America</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by Jon Robbins.<br>
